AGI - New US sanctions strike the suspension of money transfers in Cuba through Western Union, theoretically an essential source of money for the inhabitants of the communist island. But many Cubans have already turned to parallel systems that offer better exchange rates. "The Cubans always find solutions," says Yamile Garcia, a 48-year-old health worker met by AFP in old Havana. The remittances from abroad, especially from the United States, where there is a great Cuban diaspora and where many people have emigrated to escape the harsh conditions of life, are fundamental for many inhabitants of the island, which is subject to an important embargo on many products and services. Between 2005 and 2020, foreign remittances represented an annual average of 6.8% of Cuba's GDP, according to Pavel Vidal, Cuban economist and professor at the Javeriana University of Cali, Colombia.
&nbsp;
They are the second source of foreign currency of Cuba, after the medical services that the island exports worldwide. But the "official" channel, through companies like Western Union, faces a double obstacle: the recurrent US sanctions and an unfavourable official exchange rate in Cuba >. Western Union had already suspended its services in Cuba in 2020 and resumed them in 2023. The new Trump administration, after entering Cuba again on the black list of the sponsored states of terrorism (after Democrat Joe Biden had suspended the measure before leaving the White House), is in fact prohibiting some Cuban companies from carrying out financial transactions. Among these is Orbit, a company created by the Cuban government to manage transfers from abroad that, according to Washington, operates "for or on behalf of the Cuban army".
&nbsp;
Since the Cuban armed forces fall into the scope of sanctions, "so, Western Union is obliged to suspend its money transfer service between the United States and the island indefinitely," said the US company, specializing in international money transfers for individuals and companies, in a statement sent to AFP this week. The Cuban Ministry of Foreign Affairs declared in a statement that it deplored a "turn of lives on the part of the United States in their irrational hard-line policy towards the island".

