AGI - Europe moves and tries to search for a common answer to be delivered in Washington>. French President Emmanuel Macron convened for this afternoon the leaders of the main European powers, EU leaders and NATO Secretary-General, Mark Rutte, for an informal urgent meeting. The aim is to draw up a common European action plan for the peace negotiations in Ukraine. The meeting, announced on Saturday in Monaco by the Polish Foreign Minister, was only official Sunday by the head of French diplomacy, Jean-Noel Barrot.
&nbsp;
The Elysée noted that at the summit, in addition to Macron and Rutte, the heads of government of Germany, the United Kingdom, Italy, Poland, Spain, the Netherlands and Denmark will participate. At the table also the president of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, and the president of the European Council, Antònio Costa. The meeting is scheduled at 4 p.m. at Eliseo. The reduced format, in Macron's intentions, aims to guarantee an agile and unitary response to Donald Trump> and to establish what Europe can do to avoid being cut off from the peace negotiations on Ukraine.
&nbsp;
"The discussions will then continue in other formats, with the aim of bringing together all partners interested in peace and security in Europe," the European Commission said. According to Reuters and FT, the United States has already asked Europeans to specify what role they intend to play in future security guarantees that Kiev demands to prevent Putin from attacking again. The aim of the meeting, therefore, is to put on the table a common proposal, and as much as possible unitary, especially among the larger countries, while Moscow and Washington prepare for negotiation.'
&nbsp;
Already last night Trump's envoy for the Middle East, Steve Witkoff and the White House National Security Advisor, Mike Waltz, reached Saudi Arabia to talk to Russian officials at a start of negotiations, in view of a possible future meeting between Trump and Putin right in Saudi Arabia. On Saturday, General Keith Kellogg, chosen by Trump as envoy for Russia and Ukraine, made it clear that Europe will not physically sit at the negotiating table, > and Washington, as confirmed by the head of the Pentagon, Pete Hegseth during the Summit of NATO Defense Ministers, excluded the participation of American troops to a possible peacekeeping mission, idea that had been proposed by Macron a few months ago.
&nbsp;
It is therefore possible that today at the Elysée one of the points on which the seven countries The debate will be just to start thinking about the direct involvement of European forces in the field. The question now is what resources each country is willing to provide on the defence level and what Europe will ask the United States to do to maintain peace in Ukraine. The military decision will be taken by the stationaries, not in Brussels.> The Paris meeting is just the beginning.

